            width="3024"
            height="4032"
            loading="lazy"
            class="gallery-img"
          />
          <figcaption class="gallery-caption">Completed kitchen installation — Arden area, Warwickshire</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 1: Period Properties & The Arden Challenge -->
  <section class="section" style="background: var(--bg-light);">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="max-w-3xl fade-up">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">
          Fitting Kitchens in the Forest of Arden — Why Experience Matters
        </h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Henley-in-Arden sits at the heart of the ancient Forest of Arden, a landscape that gives Warwickshire some of its most characterful and distinctive housing stock. The High Street alone spans five centuries of architectural history — medieval timber-framed buildings jostle with Georgian townhouses and Victorian commercial properties converted to residential use. Beyond the town, the surrounding parishes of Beaudesert, Ullenhall, Tanworth-in-Arden, and Wootton Wawen contain substantial rural properties, working farmhouses, and converted outbuildings, many of them listed or sitting within conservation areas.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Fitting a kitchen in this context is fundamentally different from fitting one in a 1990s new-build. The walls are rarely plumb, the floors are rarely level, and the room shapes rarely conform to the rectangles that kitchen designers assume. Exposed roof timbers impose physical constraints on wall unit heights. Inglenooks and chimney breasts create alcoves that must be incorporated rather than designed around. Stone flag floors — beautiful as they are — present a level variation that no standard plinth system can hide.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          These challenges are not reasons to avoid fitting a quality kitchen in a period property. They are reasons to choose a fitter with the experience to identify them during the survey, plan around them during the design stage, and solve them on the day — rather than calling the retailer's customer service line to say the kitchen plan no longer works.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Pindi Sahota has 30 years of experience. He has fitted kitchens in properties across the full spectrum of the region's housing stock, including many of the period homes and rural conversions found across the Forest of Arden. He knows what to look for, and he knows how to handle it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: Heritage Kitchen Styles -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="max-w-3xl fade-up">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">
          Heritage and Farmhouse Kitchen Fitting Near Henley-in-Arden
        </h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          The kitchen styles popular in and around Henley-in-Arden reflect the character of the properties they are installed in. The dominant idiom is the heritage fitted kitchen — painted in-frame cabinetry in sage green, off-white, stone, or dusky blue; solid timber or granite worktops; a traditional Belfast or butler sink; and a range cooker as the architectural centrepiece of the room.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Fitting a painted in-frame kitchen is more demanding than fitting a standard framed or frameless carcass. The face frames must be perfectly aligned across the full run of units, gaps must be consistent and tight, and any deviation in the wall or floor must be absorbed invisibly into the installation rather than showing in the finished reveal. Where a shaker-door handleless kitchen forgives minor variations, an in-frame kitchen amplifies them. This is why the survey process matters so much in the Arden area — without accurate measurements and a clear understanding of the room's quirks, an in-frame kitchen cannot be ordered to the correct dimensions.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Larger rural properties in the area — farmhouses, barn conversions, and Georgian detached homes — frequently accommodate a different style: premium contemporary cabinetry, often from German manufacturers or British premium brands, with quartz or stone worktops, fully integrated appliances, and an island that serves as the social hub of an open-plan kitchen-dining-living space. These installations are technically complex and expensive to get wrong. Pindi brings the same survey-first, fixed-price approach to these projects, ensuring that the investment is protected from the outset.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
          Whatever style of kitchen you are planning — heritage shaker, contemporary handleless, or anything in between — Pindi can fit it to a high standard in a Henley-in-Arden property. Call <a href="tel:07399651836" class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--teal);">07399 651836</a> to discuss your project.
        </p>
